text: UFC 273 [ SATURDAY, APRIL 9 2022 ] The UFC returns to Jacksonville, Fla., on April 9 with two title fights atop a stacked card. The promotion on Tuesday announced the full fight lineup for the spring event, which is headlined by a featherweight title fight between champ Alexander Volkanovski and The Korean Zombie (otherwise known as Chan Sung Jung). A bantamweight title rematch between champ Aljamain Sterling and interim titleholder Petr Yan co-headlines. The title tilts were originally scheduled to headline UFC 272 on March 5, but they were moved after Volkanovski’s original opponent, ex-champ Max Holloway, was ruled out of the event. Jung stepped in as a replacement after a bevy of top featherweights called for a title shot. Sterling and Yan originally were set to meet at UFC 267, but a lingering neck injury forced Sterling to withdraw, prompting the promotion to put on an interim title fight between Yan and Cory Sandhagen, which Yan won via decision. Yan’s undisputed title was captured by Sterling via disqualification in their first meeting at UFC 258 when he landed an illegal knee that rendered Sterling unable to continue. EVENT: UFC 273: “Volkanovski vs. Korean Zombie” DATE: Sat., April 9, 2022 LOCATION: VyStar Veterans Memorial Arena in Jacksonville, Florida Alexander Volkanovski vs. Chan Sung Jung Aljamain Sterling vs. Petr Yan Mackenzie Dern vs. Tecia Torres Kelvin Gastelum vs. Nassourdine Imavov Irene Aldana vs. Aspen Ladd Preliminary Card (6:15 p.m. ET on ESPN, ESPN+ and UFC Fight Pass) Ian Garry vs. Darian Weeks Dricus Du Plessis vs. Chris Curtis Jairzinho Rozenstruik vs. Marcin Tybura Albert Duraev vs. Anthony Hernandez Mickey Gall vs. Mike Malott Gavin Tucker vs. Pat Sabatini Julio Arce vs. Daniel Santos Vinc Pichel vs. Mark Madsen Piera Rodriguez vs. Kay Hansen - https://www.mmafighting.com/2022/2/8/22924189/ufc-273-volkanovski-vs-the-korean-zombie-full-fight-card-announced

Consent is a daily practice that involves respecting personal and emotional boundaries. How can you practice consent in your daily life? - Ask for permission before you touch anyone- including family members and children- and let them know that it’s safe to say “no” if they don’t want to be touched. - Respect privacy. Don’t share information that is not yours to share. - -- Refrain from going through personal belongings without permission. - Be mindful of others’ emotional boundaries. For example, consider asking “Is it okay if we talk about this?” or “Do you have the energy to discuss this right now?” before heavy conversations. By practicing consent in everyday situations, you show others that you value their choices and limits. #SAAM2022

Sexual violence is a preventable public health issue, and everyone plays a role in ending it. What can you do today to help stop sexual violence? - Be an upstander. When you see harassment and abuse, speak up. Cancel rape jokes. - Model everyday consent, and set an example to those around you. - Seek out social-emotional learning opportunities to enhance your own relationship skills - Learn about the intersections of identity and the ways in which gender and racial inequity contribute to sexual violence - Talk to the young people in your life about healthy and unhealthy relationship behaviors

On #MLKDay, we remember the true legacy of Martin Luther King Jr. During his lifetime, he was not the darling of the establishment he is made out to be today. He refused to toe the line of the powers that be and was made to pay for it. King’s life vividly exemplifies a courageous stance against racism and the capitalist system. Read more about MLK's journey toward socialism: https://socialistrevolution.org/martin-luther-king-jr-s-journey-towards-socialism/

Although Women’s History Month is coming to an end, we will continue to celebrate women and women’s history every single day.

Want to know how to use your success for the greater good? Look no further than Thasunda Brown Duckett. As only the 2nd Black woman to lead @TIAA, a Fortune 500 firm, her work centers on financial inclusion & opportunity for millions of people. We are #BetterBecauseOfHer #WHM202

One of the most influential women in the United States, @MariaTeresa is a tireless advocate for Colombian American political rights and, more broadly, Latino rights. She is the CEO of Voto Latino, an MSNBC contributor, and a World Economic Forum Young Global Leader. In short, Teresa is a voice we count on every day — a voice we need to make sense of a world in a tough spot, and a light for Latinos everywhere. We’re #BetterBecauseOfHer.

@maziehirono is the first female senator from Hawaii and the first Asian-born immigrant elected to that post. She’s also the first Buddhist to be elected to the Senate. That’s a lot of firsts. And a lot of inspiration. Senator Hirono is known for her support and swift action on gender-based violence issues, hate crimes, and healthcare advocacy. We are #BetterBecauseOfHer

Repost @NWLC: If the wage gap doesn’t close, Black, Latina, and Native American women face lifetime losses that total nearly $1 million or more-making it impossible for them to ever catch up to what white, non-Hispanic men make in their lifetimes. #EqualPay

Today is National Equal Pay Day! Today symbolizes how far into the year the average median woman must work (in addition to their earnings last year) in order to have earned what the average median man had earned the entire previous year.

What can we say about @staceyabrams that hasn’t already been said thousands of times before? That, as a member of the Georgia House of Representatives from 2007 to 2017, Abrams made a name for herself as a fierce advocate for human rights; that she emerged not only as one of our most effective, galvanizing leaders, but as one of the most deeply inspirational women working today; that she made history by becoming the first woman and first Black woman to hold positions in both state and national politics? That we are, indisputably, #BetterBecauseOfHer

Tsai Ing-wen is the first female President of the Republic of China (Taiwan) and a member of the Taiwanese Democratic Progressive Party. She supports disadvantaged groups, favors LGBTQ+ rights, and champions bipartisanship, labor reform, and green energy. What can’t she do? Not only are the people of Taiwan #BetterBecauseOfHer — we all are.

Not just anyone can be the youngest person ever awarded the Nobel Peace Prize. “I tell my story not because it is unique,” says @Malala, “but because it is the story of so many girls.” We are #BetterBecauseOfHer. #WHM2022

Happy #Juneteenth! On June 19, 1865, when enslaved people in Galveston, Texas received word that the war had ended and that all enslaved people were now free...which was over two years after the signing of the Emancipation Proclamation. Today, we honor and celebrate Black liberation — with the understanding that freedom and justice have always been delayed for Black people in the United States. And for allies: a Juneteenth challenge for you. Today and throughout the week, we'll be sharing tangible action steps you can take right now to advance equity, justice, and freedom for all: https://bit.ly/3N2D7Hy:=:https://www.ywcacolumbus.org/juneteenth-celebrate-black-freedom-and-fight-against-racism/ None of us are free until all of us are free.

We're two days into this week's challenge and are learning so much about Understanding Reproductive Justice. Have you seen today’s challenge about sex education? What schools teach about sex, relationships, and our bodies looks different everywhere and reflects the beliefs and values of the culture in which we are raised. However, regardless of where we grow up and from whom we learn, knowing the basic facts about our body's work is critical for our health and safety, particularly for women and girls. Learn about how comprehensive sex education helps create equality and form healthy relationships. We'd like to thank our presenting partner, Football UNITES™, a program of the Miami Dolphins. We’re halfway through the Stand Against Racism Challenge. During Week 3, we're discussing Understanding Reproductive Justice with today’s discussion about period poverty. Each month, individuals who menstruate need access to hygiene products and resources, but these are not always accessible. Period poverty is inadequate access to period products and menstrual cycle education. Even in the wealthiest country in the world, people do not have the essentials they need, especially if they are a part of marginalized communities. Stacey Abrams is an American politician, lawyer, businesswoman, and writer who served in the Georgia House of Representatives from 2007 to 2017, becaming the first Black Minority Leader in the House in 2011. While in office Abrams began the New Georgia Project, an initiative that worked to register voters, particularly young people and people of color. In 2018, she began an organization called Fair Fight to protect voter’s rights. Abrams is credited with adding thousands of democratic voters in Georgia. Thank you, Stacey Abrams, for your continued work to give a voice back to the under served and unrepresented members of the community.

Happy Juneteenth! JUVA celebrates the liberation of black people from Slavery! Juneteenth is also known as Freedom Day, Jubilee Day, Liberation Day, and Emancipation Day – is a holiday celebrating the emancipation of those who had been enslaved in the United States. In 1865, when federal troops arrived in Galveston, Texas, to take control of the state and ensure that all enslaved people were freed, slaves began to celebrate Juneteenth. The troops' arrival came a full two and a half years after the signing of the Emancipation Proclamation. Juneteenth honors the end of Slavery in the United States and is considered the longest-running African American holiday. JUVA stands with our black community and supports Juneteenth. #happyjuneteenth #freedom #federalholiday #equality #nyc #dermatology #juneteenth #aestheticmedicine #hope #Boardcertifieddermatologist #holiday #weareinthistogether

Nakahama Manjirō is considered America’s first Japanese immigrant, arriving in the country in May of 1843. Read more about Manjirō’s life below: Nakahama Manjirō was born in Japan on January 27, 1827. He became the man of the family at the age of 8 after his father passed away and at fourteen years old, he started working on a fishing boat. On January 13, 1841 the fishing boat was caught in a terrible storm causing it to crash into Tori-shima Island. Manjirō and the other fisherman were stranded on the island until June 27 when a whaling ship, captained by William Whitfield, spotted the men and came to their aid. While boarding Captain Whitfield’s boat, they realized they could not communicate with each other and began using hand gestures to communicate. For the next few months, the men sailed the North Pacific waters catching whales until they finally docked in Oahu in the Sandwich Islands (Hawaii). When preparing to leave, Captain Whitfield asked Manjirō to continue sailing with him to America. Manjirō and Captain Whitfield arrived in Fairhaven, Massachusetts in May 1843 (age 16). On May 16, 1846, three years after settling in America, Manjirō decided to set sail and head back home to Japan. After a couple of setbacks, Manjirō arrived to his hometown in January of 1851 where he was welcomed home by his mother. After his arrival home, Manjirō was named a samurai and worked as a political emissary between his home country and the West. Manjirō suffered a mild stoke in 1871, which did permanent damage to his body. Later in 1898, he died in his son’s home at age 71. #AAPIHeritageMonth #AsianAmericanHeritage #PacificIslanderHeritage

O Allah we thank you for giving us more life and more time and more opportunity to do good deeds and to please you and the opportunity to earn the Paradise. So many have Died and have went ahead of us and we will also go ahead of others also. Lot of things going on as usual, with a lot of Deaths and people Dying and many Janazahs in last few days and last week and more lined up for the next few days. Subhanallah so many Deaths it is just overwhelming. All of them emotional, tragic and sad for their family and friends. Our Janazah last Tuesday was for Joshua Dreyling, from St Paul. He was a Revert brother who embraced Islam few years ago. He tragically Died last week and we buried him last Tuesday. Though his family was Catholic, they allowed us to bury him and give him a proper Janazah. His family was very thankful and appreciative of the preparation and burial he was given. They said: "We are grateful and thankful to the Muslims for taking such good care of him and standing by us during this difficult time." Alhamdulillah we were able to bury him as a Muslim. Alhamdulillah they also have a friend who is a Muslim and so they are very respectful of Islam and may be even be close to becoming Muslim. They have utmost respect for Islam and Muslims. And this Janazah has brought them even closer. They appreciated the Janazah and the few Muslims who came for the Janazah. Of course they had a large turnout of family and friends. Unfortunately not many Muslims came, inspite of being informed and encouraged to come. It seems our Reverts are left alone and abandoned when they Die and hardly nobody comes for their Janazah. We always inform the community that only their non-Muslim family will come for their Janazah, so it is important that we come out to not only fulfill our Duty and Responsibility, but to also show our concern and support for our fellow Muslim brother or Sister. Unfortunately we haven't understood or realized how important it is or that it is a DUTY AND RESPONSIBILITY IN ISLAM. KNOWN AS FARD KIFAYAH. So many times our Reverts are not given Janazah and are buried as Christians or even Cremated. So we don't realize how important it is to stand by and support our Revert brothers and sisters. So many times we have to fight and struggle to get their bodies and to make sure that they get a Janazah and buried as a Muslim. And the least and small thing we can do is to come to their Janazah. The opposite scenario is a high profile Janazah of a person who Died and from a big Qabeela, or was well known in the community, or just a high profile case of a tragic murder or accident, and out of curiosity everybody feels that they need to come. Then the turn out is Overwhelming. As we know Islam is not about Qabeela, Tribe, Country or Nationality, but is about what really joins us together, La illaha illallah, Muhammadur Rasoolullah. The Prophet also said " A Muslim is a brother to his brother Muslim." And the real issue is if we never come for others how do we expect others to come for us. And now we also have another Revert brother that also Died few days ago. His Janazah will be in few days. He also does not have Muslim family, so looks like he will also be buried alone wiith no one to come for his Janazah. This is the sad state that we see over and over again, that people don't seem to feel brotherhood or any connection with our Revert brothers who have taken Shahadah. Alhamdulillah a few people always do show up, but not many. Perhaps last time we saw maybe 8 or 10 people. Alhamdulillah, may Allah reward them for their time and effort in coming. May Allah grant them a high place in Jannah. For they fulfilled the Obligation and Responsibility of the 200,000 Muslims of the Twincities.

WCC is celebrating Asian Pacific American Heritage Month! Hiram Fong, one of Hawaii’s first two senators, became the first Asian Pacific American to serve in the U.S. Senate in 1959. Seven others have followed in his historic footsteps: Samuel Hayakawa of California (1977-1983); Spark Matsunaga (1977-1990), Daniel Inouye (1963-2012), and Daniel Akaka (1990-2013), all of Hawaii; and current senators Mazie Hirono of Hawaii, Tammy Duckworth of Illinois, and Kamala Harris of California, current Vice President of the United States.

WCC is celebrating Women's History Month: Bessie Coleman was the first African American and Native American, woman to pilot a plane. “Brave Bessie” thrilled audiences with her daring aerial tricks, as she looped and barrel-rolled her way into the hearts of cheering crowds across the country. She traveled the country giving flight lessons, performing in-flight shows, and she encouraged African Americans and women to learn how to fly. She also refused to perform anywhere that African Americans were not welcome.

WCC is celebrating Black History Month: Dr. Shirley Jackson, the first African American woman to earn a doctorate at MIT, is responsible for monumental telecommunications research that led to the invention of products, such as the touch-tone phone, portable fax, fiber optic cables, and caller ID. Dr. Jackson was inducted into the National Women’s Hall of Fame in 1998 for her contributions as a distinguished scientist and advocate for education, science, and public policy.

The answer to Tuesday's night trivia question is A.! The reduction of forests combined with hunting/poaching, have greatly displaced these animals. Bison, elk, and wolves require a lot of space and food sources which much of our urban and agricultural landscapes cannot support. There are some black bears further south, but their numbers are so low that they are considered endangered statewide. Mountain lions, also called cougars, often travel searching for mates or hunting territory and could possibly pass through Ohio. But there hasn't been an established population and mountain lions are considered locally extinct throughout the Eastern United States. 🐺🦌🐻

#BlackHistoryMonth Spotlight on Matiki Anoff. Matiki Anoff (Matiki Pro Makeup) is a makeup artist whose credits include Spider-Man: Far From Home, Men in Black: International, and Love Beaty Rhymes. Additionally, she was the Makeup Department Head of Netflix’s Ma Rainey’s Black Bottom. She designed all of the background makeup looks, including the look of Taylour Paige as Dussie Mae. #MaRainey #MaRaineyFilm #MakeupDepartmentHead #Makeup #MUA #BehindTheScenes #Film

#BlackHistoryMonth Spotlight on Cheryl Dunye. Cheryl Dunye is a world-renowned filmmaker who created 1996's The Watermelon Woman, the first film written by a Black lesbian exploring Black lesbianism in cinema history. She first emerged as part of the “Queer New Wave” of young filmmakers in the early 1990s and her work has since cemented the influence for many queer creatives today. You can see her latest directorial work in HBO's Lovecraft Country, Delilah, and upcoming season of Bridgerton. #TheWatermelonWoman #LovecraftCountry #CW4400 #Filmmaker

#BlackHistoryMonth Spotlight on Angie Wells. Makeup Department Head Angie Wells is known for her historical accurate makeup in films such as Mudbound, Harriet, and Sylvie’s Love. Additionally, she has recently worked on Promising Young Woman and the upcoming Cheaper by the Dozen film.Throughout her career, Angie has been very outspoken about the need for makeup and hair film crews that understand how to work with dark skin tones and Black hair. In 2020, she was selected as one of Variety’s Artisans Elite Report, as one of the creatives behind the best crafts of the year. #Mudbound #Harriet #SylviesLove #PromisingYoungWoman #CheaperbytheDozen #Film #Makeup #MUA #BehindTheScenes
